{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39638dc7-ed5b-4441-b455-4be899c7cb69","content":"No worries — I don't need to inspect the project to answer this. Here's how to configure it:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your server. Adjust the path if needed.\n- If your server uses environment variables, add an `\"env\"` object alongside `\"args\"`.\n- Make sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout using the MCP protocol (e.g., via the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package with `stdio` transport).\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot chat panel in **Agent mode** — it will auto-discover and connect to your server's tools.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"827f3647-1abe-458f-ab03-c7383aa34ee1","outputTokens":287,"requestId":"AC19:3988B0:B57AAA:E1233E:6A012D17"},"id":"4af245cb-2a53-45c9-a6dd-540471ce8ab4","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:13:05.833Z","parentId":"823675c3-b581-439c-8798-c477f91d9cac"}
